<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18360509-1369">
               <interp inst="t18360509-1369" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18360509"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18360509-1369" type="date" value="18360509"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18360509-1369-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1369-18360509 t18360509-1369-offence-1 t18360509-1369-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1369. <persName id="def1-1369-18360509" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1369-18360509" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1369-18360509" type="age" value="22"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1369-18360509" type="surname" value="ALTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1369-18360509" type="given" value="ISAAC"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ISAAC ALTON</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18360509-1369-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18360509-1369-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18360509-1369-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="theftFromPlace"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18360509-cd-210" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1369-offence-1 t18360509-cd-210"></join>17th of April</rs> 4 hams, value 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18360509-name-1459" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1459" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1459" type="surname" value="HUMPHERY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1459" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1459" type="occupation" value="private watchman"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1369-offence-1 t18360509-name-1459"></join>John Humphery</persName>, being on a wharf ad<lb></lb>jacent to a certain navigable river.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1460" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1460" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1460" type="surname" value="HUTCHINGS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1460" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES HUTCHINGS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am private watchman to Mr. Hunpherys: his name is John. I do not exactly know whether there is an a to his some or not to it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1461" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1461" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1461" type="surname" value="THOROGOOD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1461" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD THOROGOOD</persName>
                  </hi>. I do not know Hutchings—I do not know what ward he is watchman to—I know a gentleman of the name of John Has<lb></lb>phery—he is proprietor of Haye's Wharf, Tooley-street—I mean the Alderman—his wagons are over London-bridge continually.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do not wagoners and carters often go on a wharf which they do not belong to? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I only know the what belongs to him by taking letters directed to him, to the hotel at the end of our bridge—I do not know what connexion the hotel has with the wharf.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1462" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1462" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1462" type="surname" value="HUTCHINGS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1462" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES HUTCHINGS</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined</hi>. My master is Mr. Alderman Humphery, and he owns Haye's wharf. On Sunday morning, about quarter past four o'clock, I came on shore from the tier of vessels on the wharf—my business in on board ship and on shore—I came from <hi rend="italic">The Lord Glenlyon</hi>—I found the prisoner concealed between some hogsheads of hams—which were lying on the cast side of Haye's Wharf—he was lying on his belly, and three hams were lying on his feet, between two and three yards from a hogshead which was broken open—he pretended to be intoxicated, but was not—I secured him of stealing these hams—he told me he only meant to take one—I said I should lock him up, and asked him what hogshead was broken open, and where the hams came from—he went and shewed me the hogshead that was broken open, and told me the hams came out of that—the hogshead was lying with the heads pressed out, and the hams strewed about—there ought to have been forty-eight hams in the hogshead, and there were forty-three—those at his feet seemed to correspond with those in the hogshead.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say he was not drunk? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I will swear it—he had not the opportunity to go off with them, because I came upon him so quickly—I had been there about two hours before—he could not have been there an hour and a half, because the vessel he was on board, was not in berth till twenty or thirty minutes before I found him—I put the vessel in myself, so that there was not time to go and break open the hogshead and take the hams on board a ship—I know two hams were found on board, he had not time to take the five hams away—he had not time to take a third ham on board—his ship laid about ten yards from the place—he could not have taken five hams and put them on board the vessel—he pretended to have been asleep—I came on him too quickly for him to walk off to the vessel—he was lying on his belly between the hogsheads, and the hams lay on the back part of his legs—he could have placed them there very easily—it would be the readiest way to get them out from between the hogsheads—there was a visitor on board the ship, named West—the captain and mate were down aft, West was walking</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090259"></xptr>
               <p>the deck and took him into custody—I told him he might come and clear himself—he had no business to be there as he did not belong to the ship—he came to visit the prisoner on the might before—I knew the berth in which West slept—I found one ham in his berth and Alton's—West has got no berth on board the ship—the captain told me he was a visitor—I found a ham underneath the prisoner's bed—it was not a berth—it was a lumber<lb></lb>place—the captain and the mate told me it was the prisoner's berth.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You found three hams on his legs, and he said he meant only to steal one? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He did, and he showed me the cask from whence he took them—the hams were wanted to go away, and four were returned which are not here.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1463" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1463" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1463" type="surname" value="TAYLOR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1463" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE TAYLOR</persName>
                  </hi>. I was called—I had just done swinging the vessels—the witness pointed out the man lying on his belly, with three hams on his legs—Hutchings called him out, and asked what he was going to do—he said he intended to take one ham, if he had not come so quick upon him—Hutchings asked him where he got the hams from—he said they came out of the hogshead—Hutchings said, "Show me the hogshead they came out of"—he got in between the hogsheads, and showed him—he was quite sober, but tried to appear drunk.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How could a man, lying on his belly, put three hams on his legs, when he had not room to move himself? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He could put them over his shoulder, on his legs—his head might be a yard and a half from the hogshead which was lying on its bilge—the hams were all shot out—some of them were lying close to his hand—he could not get out say other way than by putting them on his legs—he had not room to turn himself—he was obliged to back himself out astern.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1464" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1464" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1464" type="surname" value="LEGG"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1464" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM LEGG</persName>
                  </hi>. I am warehouseman to Mr. Humphery. I saw these hogshead safe on Saturday night, between nine and ten o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Whose property were these while they were an Mr. Humphery's wharf? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They belonged to him—I call him Alderson John Humphery.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. I was drunk between twelve and one o'clock, and do not know how I came there.</p>
               <p>(Robert Johnson, the prisoner's brother-in-law, gave him a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18360509-1369-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-1369-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-1369-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 22.—
